          "content": "It's important to understand that not every group of people needs to operate as a team. There are two main types of groups: working groups and true teams. Working groups are designed to coordinate the efforts of individuals. In these groups, each person is responsible for their own tasks, and there is no need for shared accountability or collaboration among members. This means that while everyone is working hard, they are not necessarily working together towards a common goal.\nOn the other hand, true teams are different. They come together to collaborate and create results that are much greater than what any single person could achieve on their own. In a true team, members share responsibility and work closely together, combining their skills and ideas to innovate and solve problems.\nAs a leader, it is crucial to evaluate the nature of the task at hand. You must determine whether it is better suited for a team or a working group. If you force teamwork on tasks that are meant for individual contributions, it can lead to wasted time and frustration. Conversely, if you treat tasks that require collaboration as individual work, you risk losing out on the creativity and innovative solutions that can arise from true teamwork. Understanding these distinctions can help you lead more effectively and achieve better outcomes for your group.\nContext recap: It's important to understand that not every group of people needs to operate as a team. There are two main types of groups: working groups and true teams. Working groups are designed to coordinate the efforts of individuals. In these groups, each person is responsible for their own tasks, and there is no need for shared accountability or collaboration among members.\nWhy this matters: Working Groups vs. True Teams helps learners in Business connect ideas from Leading Teams & Organizations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
