          "content": "Providing effective feedback is a crucial part of helping individuals and teams grow and improve. When giving feedback, it is important to be specific, timely, focused on observable behaviors, and aimed at encouraging growth. One helpful method for delivering feedback is the SBI model, which stands for Situation-Behavior-Impact. This model guides you to first describe the situation where the behavior occurred, then identify the specific behavior you observed, and finally explain the impact that behavior had on the team or project. This approach helps keep the feedback objective and constructive. It is also essential to avoid labeling someone's character traits, as this can lead to defensiveness and hinder growth. A good practice is to balance positive feedback, which highlights what someone is doing well and should continue, with constructive feedback, which points out areas for improvement. Creating an environment where feedback is welcomed from all directions — whether from supervisors to team members, from team members to supervisors, or among peers — is vital for fostering a culture of continuous improvement. Research by Marcial Losada shows that high-performing teams maintain a positive interaction ratio of about three positive comments for every negative one. This balance helps to build trust and encourages open communication, making it easier for everyone to learn and grow together.\nContext recap: Providing effective feedback is a crucial part of helping individuals and teams grow and improve. When giving feedback, it is important to be specific, timely, focused on observable behaviors, and aimed at encouraging growth. One helpful method for delivering feedback is the SBI model, which stands for Situation-Behavior-Impact. This model guides you to first describe the situation where the behavior occurred, then identify the specific behavior you observed, and finally explain the impact that behavior had on the team or project.\nWhy this matters: Giving Developmental Feedback helps learners in Business connect ideas from Leading Teams & Organizations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
