          "id": "leadership-301-l04-c2",
          "title": "Building Trust Remotely",
          "content": "Building trust within virtual teams is essential for success and involves two key components: cognitive trust and affective trust. Cognitive trust refers to the confidence that team members have in each other's abilities and reliability. This type of trust can be developed by leaders who set clear expectations for their team members, consistently follow through on their commitments, and maintain transparency about how performance is tracked. When team members know what is expected of them and see that their leaders are reliable, they are more likely to trust one another.\nOn the other hand, affective trust is about the emotional connections and care that team members have for each other. To cultivate this type of trust, leaders should actively invest in building relationships within the team. This can be done through engaging activities such as virtual coffee chats, where team members can casually connect, personal check-ins to show that leaders care about their well-being, and celebrating achievements together, no matter how small. Additionally, creating informal spaces for social interaction, like virtual game nights or team-building exercises, can help strengthen these bonds.\nResearch shows that teams that focus on relationship-building during their onboarding process and in the early stages of projects tend to outperform those that concentrate solely on completing tasks. By prioritizing trust and relationships, virtual teams can enhance collaboration and achieve better results together.\nContext recap: Building trust within virtual teams is essential for success and involves two key components: cognitive trust and affective trust. Cognitive trust refers to the confidence that team members have in each other's abilities and reliability. This type of trust can be developed by leaders who set clear expectations for their team members, consistently follow through on their commitments, and maintain transparency about how performance is tracked. When team members know what is expected of them and see that their leaders are reliable, they are more likely to trust one another.\nWhy this matters: Building Trust Remotely helps learners in Business connect ideas from Leading Teams & Organizations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
